<DOC><DOCNO> AP890619-0175 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 1925EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-19 0477</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0491</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms, From The Gulf To The Great Lakes</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Showers and thunderstorms spread across the South and north tothe Great Lakes on Monday, with heavy rain causing flooding inAlabama, and temperatures reached record highs across the westernPlains.   Afternoon showers and thunderstorms extended from northwesternFlorida across southeastern Louisiana and north into Wisconsin,Lower Michigan, Indiana and Ohio. Showers and thunderstorms alsowere scattered over southern Florida and western Texas.   A storm poured rain on eastern Alabama at a rate of more than 1inch an hour, sending creeks across rural roads and forcingofficials to open flood gates on the Lake Martin reservoir on theTallapoosa River for the first time since 1984.   Some roads were washed out, state police reported.   Lightning during the storm sparked minor fires at two houses inDadeville, which received 6 inches of rain, the National WeatherService said. Montgomery got 1.85 inches of rain in the six hours upto 2 p.m. EDT.   In Houston County, authorities said high wind downed trees andpower lines at Cottonwood and in the community of Webb.   In Florida, }-inch-diameter hail fell northeast of Tallahasseeand wind gusted to 76 mph at the Tallahassee airport.   Thunderstorm wind gusts caused damage near Whitmire, S.C., atWebb and Cottonwood, Ala., and near Sharon, Ga., the weather servicesaid.   Locally heavy rain also fell in the central Lower Michigancounties of Isabella and Montcalm, with as much as 2.61 inches atBlanchard during a four-hour period, the weather service said.   Elsewhere, showers developed over the northern Pacific Coast.   Temperatures reached 90 degrees and hotter by early afternoonfrom Minnesota across North Dakota.   Across the western Plains, reports of record highs included 94 atColorado Springs, Colo.; 98 at Denver, and 102 at Scottsbluff, Neb.Denver's previous record of 96 had stood since 1880.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 52degrees at Seattle to 110 at Tucson, Ariz. Monday's low temperaturefor the Lower 48 states was 37 degrees at West Yellowstone, Mont.   For Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from NewYork state across southern New England, and from New Jersey andPennsylvania across Florida, Alabama, southeastern Mississippi andsoutheastern Louisiana. Showers were forecast along the northernPacific Coast.   Highs were predicted in the 60s from western Montana across thenorthern Pacific Coast; near 90 over the Mississippi Valley andNorth Dakota; in the 90s in Florida, from South Dakota across Texas,from much of Wyoming across New Mexico, and in the central sectionof southern California; 100 degrees and hotter from inlandsouth-central Texas across western Texas and the Texas Panhandle;from 100 to near 120 from southern and western Arizona acrosssoutheastern California and southern Nevada. Temperatures wereexpected generally in the 70s and 80s over the remainder of thenation.</TEXT></DOC>